Anonymous Thu 09 Mar 2023 13:46:31 No.54935743 Report
Quoted By:
>>54934649
don't lore dump, period
If you do it in conversation, you're likely to veer into "As you know..." or "You really should know..." territory. A better way is to introduce a single concept in as few words as possible, then let the reader see the results quickly.
Lore dumps are a big pause button on pacing if they are inside a conversation. Not quite as bad is a part of a scene centered around a character thinking, but whether it's in first or third person, it fails unless the character is reacting to a just-shown example of the lore.

The way I handled it in what I'm working on, for a group that you don't see until the halfway point, is that they are built up out of single sentence observations. Readers that know the source get it, but those that don't will understand the second that scene starts. All those asides and remarks weren't jokes.
And as a bonus, it lets the first half of the story focus on the four main characters and why they fail to overcome this group in the initial contact.
